Event.title: The Last Supper
Event.short_desctipion: Millers O’Brien Gallery presents artist Raul Ortega Ayala’s authentic recreation of The Last Supper
Event.long_description: Wellington’s newest contemporary art gallery, Millers O’Brien, teams up with New Zealand-based Mexican artist Raul Ortega Ayala to recreate The Last Supper. This one-night-only experience takes you on an authentic exploration of history's most depicted meal. Ayala prepares and serves a five-course meal accompanied by Galilean wine, while enacting the rituals likely to have been experienced by the 12 Apostles. If you’re seated at the table be prepared to take centre stage – your dining experience will be filmed before an audience. The dinner and film will become part of Ayala’s first NZ solo exhibition, Food for Thought, opening at the gallery the following Friday.

Event.title: The Last Supper: Food for Thought Exhibition
Event.short_desctipion: Millers O’Brien Gallery presents artist Raul Ortega Ayala’s first NZ solo show Food for Thought
Event.long_description: Wellington’s newest contemporary art gallery, Millers O’Brien, and New Zealand-based Mexican artist Raul Ortega Ayala recreate The Last Supper. This multi-layered art-performance piece evolves in two stages: on Fri 10 Aug Ayala will serve the notorious meal to 12 ticket holders (see here for tickets), which you can watch live. From Fri 17 Aug, the filmed meal forms the basis of Ayala’s first solo NZ exhibition, Food for Thought. The exhibition features other works including Tomatina-Tim, a video installation depicting thousands of revellers throwing tomatoes at one another and an American professional ‘gurgitator’ that consumes 40 hotdogs in ten minutes.

Your ticket includes a donation to Kahurangi School for their new orchard, entry to the screening and Q+A, a forage themed cocktail, and Coco's Garden Bed - our head chef’s interpretation of an edible garden bed. Event.title: Hiakai Hāngi
Event.short_desctipion: Five top Kiwi and international chefs will gather around the hāngi pit to create a four-course feast
Event.long_description:
A traditional hāngi but not as you know it. Five top Kiwi and international chefs and foodies will gather around the hāngi pit in a celebration of Polynesian culture and culinary traditions passed down through generations. Four course of slow-cooked kai, accompanied by Tutū cider, Kono and Tohu wine and entertainment will be served up at dusk, overlooking the Wellington Harbour. Featuring Michael Meredith (AKL), Ron Finley (LA), Morgan McGlone (MEL), James Knappett (UK), led by Wellington's own Monique Fiso, the Hiakai Hāngi is proudly presented by Kono.
• Michael Meredith, based in Auckland, has been the leading force behind the eponymously named Meredith’s for a decade and three years ago became involved in the social enterprise, Eat My Lunch. Michael is also an Air New Zealand consultant chef.
• Ron Finley is one of the United States most widely known food activists. Frustrated by his community’s lack of access to fresh, organic food, Finley inadvertently started a revolution when he turned the grass verge in front of his South-Central L.A. home into an edible garden in 2010. His Ted Talk has had over 3.1 million views and he’ll be here for Visa WOAP
• Morgan McGlone hails from the Hawkes Bay but is now based in Melbourne where he oversees his restaurants Belles Hot Chicken (Melbourne and Sydney) along with the recently opened, Natural History in Melbourne. Morgan spent several years working for Sean Brock at Husk in South Carolina, and then as Chef de Cuisine at Husk, Nashville.
• James Knappett of Bubbledogs and Kitchen Table in London has worked at some of the world’s most highly-regarded and celebrated restaurants. Having spent time in the kitchens at The Ledbury (two Michelin stars) and at The Berkeley (also two stars), James has also worked under at Royal Hospital Road (three stars) and Rick Stein’s The Seafood Restaurant in Padstow. James worked for two-years in the kitchen at the World’s Best Restaurant Noma (two stars) and at NYC restaurant, Per Se (three stars).
• Monique Fiso leads the Hiakai Hangi. From an after-school job as a sandwich hand at the tender age of 14, to the Michelin-starred kitchens of New York City. Monique Fiso always wanted to be a chef. Completing her studies at the Wellington Institute of Technology and while still in school talked her way into her first fine dining job working for Chef Martin Bosley at the eponymous Martin Bosley at the Port Nicholson Yacht Club - the number one ranking restaurant in New Zealand at that time. With a hunger for adventure and a desire for a challenge, Fiso booked a ticket to New York City, home of some of the world’s best restaurants. Fiso headed for Michelin starred PUBLIC restaurant and was immediately put to work. Over the next seven years, Fiso honed her skills as a sous chef in some of New York City's top kitchens - The Musket Room, PUBLIC Restaurant, A Voce, Saxon+Parole, Double Crown, to name a few. Venue.description:
Due to the size of the “not-your-usual” commercial open space that we need we are yet to confirm a venue. We want this to be a space that is not something the public would normally have access to. Last’s year’s amazing ex-Unilever Factory venue is our benchmark and it’s likely we can secure it again – but this is based on it being vacant outside of any future potential commercial lease.
We are also looking at Avalon TV Studios, the ex-Ford Factory in Seaview (now Placemakers) and other warehouse spaces we can turn in to a lab. We’ll book a back-up inside venue in case we need to use it. 
Ideally we will be able to confirm this as tickets go on sale so it is clear cut for ticketholders, however if we need to again the mystery location for last year's event did work well as a marketing tactic.
